Between lettuce which are half way through the cropping season, with another five weeks still of harvest to come from them, I am sowing carrots for autumn. This is fourth of June and it’s a great time over the next two weeks to sow  wherever you can find space. By mid July the lettuce will finish and I twist them out, and the carrots then fill all the space quite quickly. This is no dig and easy and quick.

node.text: After humid weather - and we put all blighted material on the compost heap

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 17, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: Close/companion planting of multisown leeks and beetroot, intersown carrots and interplanted kale, all second plantings with no compost added since December and no feeds given. No dig bed front and dig bed behind, growth more similar than in previous years perhaps from having the sides removed, allowing plants in the dug soil to access fungi rich soil in the pathways. Path soil is an important asset - feed it, keep weed free without using membrane and here we just pull occasional weed seedlings, it’s full of plant roots.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 14, 2021. May be an image of tree and outdoors.

node.text: I’m a happy gardener - growth is good, weeds are few and the compost heaps keep filling. We just posted a new video about three types of compost heap on my You Tube channel.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 13, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: Bed planted and covered, has some winter radish as well as the pak choi. Rapid bed prep with no dig, and we add no extra compost or feeds for second and third plantings

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 13, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: Tonight I’m chatting on IG Live with @clausdalby about no dig,, and growing lots of plants in small spaces. Claus has just written a comprehensive book Krukke  Kokkenhaven on growing in containers (in Danish). In this bed we harvested the last celery yesterday, and I’m about to dib small holes for the plants of Pak Choi sown just two weeks ago, which we shall then cover with mesh against insects. We are live at 6pm British / 7pm European time

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 11, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: We’ve had good rain and the greens are green! Brussels sprouts are promising for October onwards, kale is yielding loads and carrots sown 4th June (under mesh against root fly) are almost ready - all second plantings after carrot, lettuce and spinach. My new book appearing January is Skills for Successful Growing and we got some lovely photos for it this morning with the incredible @jasoningram

node.text: Two fine helpers for a few days @adam_bowers_uk and @ateenandhistrowel, both growing no dig at home already. Adam is tipping shredded hedge prunings to compost and Jamie is edging with long handled shears

node.text: I love the underestimated beauty in vegetable gardens! Even with the white covers which in this case are protecting carrots from root fly, and salads from rabbits. My favourite flowers now are the summer zinnias, sown undercover in April with marigolds as well, sunflowers sown early May undercover and dahlias which survive winter here as bulbs in the ground, from @sarahravensgarden originally as seed. #nodig helps because we build the beauty instead of needing to weed, see my no dig online course and book on website. Today is a day course here and I hope the sunshine continues, but think it may not!!
